  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Book of Changes
  author: Kwon Geon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the clean daylight, not a speck of dust disturbs the desk,
    while tendrils of incense rise straight from the censer's glow.
    I grind vermillion ink and mark all sixty-four hexagrams,
    seeking gain and loss within each traced line.
    Sitting upright through the morning, lost in deep contemplation,
    I come to see, line by line, the heart of heaven.
    This is why Confucius wore through his book's cords thrice—
    for one eternal truth shines through both past and present.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The sixty-four hexagrams refer to the complete system of divination in the I Ching (Book of Changes).
  - key: ''
    value: Confucius 'wore through the cords' of the I Ching repeatedly—a classical expression meaning he studied it so intensely that the binding wore out, emphasizing his devotion to understanding its wisdom.
